Let's substitute $f(x)=e^x$ and $t=e$ into the second expression to find the appropriate limit expression for $f'(e)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{f(t+h)-f(t)}{h}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{e^{t+h}-e^t}{h}&&\small\gray{\text{Substitute }f(x)=e^x}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{e^{e+h}-e^e}{h}&&\small\gray{\text{Substitute }t=e}
\end{align}$

Let's substitute $g(x)=\log(x)$ and $t=2$ into the second expression to find the appropriate limit expression for $g'(2)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{g(t+h)-g(t)}{h}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{\log(t+h)-\log(t)}{h}&&\small{\gray{\text{Substitute }g(x)=\log(x)}}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{\log(2+h)-\log(2)}{h}&&\small{\gray{\text{Substitute }t=2}}
\end{align}$

Let's substitute $f(x)=\dfrac{1}{x}$ and $t=1$ into the second expression to find the appropriate limit expression for $f'(1)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{f(t+h)-f(t)}{h}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{\dfrac{1}{t+h}-\dfrac{1}{t}}{h}&&\small{\gray{\text{Substitute }f(x)=\dfrac{1}{x}}}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{\dfrac{1}{1+h}-\dfrac{1}{1}}{h}&&\small\gray{\text{Substitute }t=1}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{\dfrac{1}{1+h}-1}{h}&&\small\gray{\text{Simplify }}
\end{align}$

Let's substitute $g(x)=x^2$ and $t=3$ into the second expression to find the appropriate limit expression for $g'(3)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{g(t+h)-g(t)}{h}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{(t+h)^2-t^2}{h}&&\small{\gray{\text{Substitute }g(x)=x^2}}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{(3+h)^2-3^2}{h}&&\small{\gray{\text{Substitute }t=3}}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{(3+h)^2-9}{h}&&\small{\gray{\text{Simplify }}}
\end{align}$

Let's substitute $f(x)=\sin(x)$ and $t=\dfrac{\pi}{2}$ into the first expression to find the appropriate limit expression for $f'\left(\dfrac{\pi}{2}\right)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to t}\dfrac{f(x)-f(t)}{x-t}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to t}\dfrac{\sin(x)-\sin(t)}{x-t}&&\small\gray{\text{Substitute }f(x)=\sin(x)}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to \small\dfrac{\pi}{2}}\dfrac{\sin(x)-\sin\left(\dfrac{\pi}{2}\right)}{x-\dfrac{\pi}{2}}&&\small\gray{\text{Substitute }t=\dfrac{\pi}{2 }}
\end{align}$

Let's substitute $g(x)=\cos(x)$ and $t=\pi$ into the first expression to find the appropriate limit expression for $g'\left(\pi\right)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to t}\dfrac{g(x)-g(t)}{x-t}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to t}\dfrac{\cos(x)-\cos(t)}{x-t}&&\small\gray{\text{Substitute }g(x)=\cos(x)}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to \pi}\dfrac{\cos(x)-\cos\left(\pi\right)}{x-\pi}&&\small\gray{\text{Substitute }t=\pi}
\end{align}$

Let's substitute $f(x)=\sqrt{x}$ and $t=4$ into the first expression to find the appropriate limit expression for $f'\left(4\right)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to t}\dfrac{f(x)-f(t)}{x-t}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to t}\dfrac{\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{t}}{x-t}&&\small\gray{\text{Substitute }f(x)=\sqrt{x}}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 4}\dfrac{\sqrt{x}-\sqrt{4}}{x-4}&&\small\gray{\text{Substitute }t=4}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 4}\dfrac{\sqrt{x}-2}{x-4}
\end{align}$

Let's substitute $g(x)=\ln(x)$ and $t=5$ into the first expression to find the appropriate limit expression for $g'\left(5\right)$:

$\begin{align}
&\phantom{=}\displaystyle\lim_{x\to t}\dfrac{g(x)-g(t)}{x-t}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to t}\dfrac{\ln(x)-\ln(t)}{x-t}&&\small\gray{\text{Substitute }g(x)=\ln(x)}
\\\\
&=\displaystyle\lim_{x\to 5}\dfrac{\ln(x)-\ln\left(5\right)}{x-5}&&\small\gray{\text{Substitute }t=5}
\end{align}$
